The report further noted that women in the West African community believed that being a divorcee would single them out for scorn in Nigerian society.

The study warns that the experiences described by Nigerian women are likely to be experienced by other women across other West African communities.

The author said: “Certain links can be observed more broadly. For example, the protection of women’s rights not only influences reproductive decisions, but the chances that women enjoy and are able to play an effective role in public life. The participation of women in politics across English-speaking West African states (Ghana, Sierra Leone, and Nigeria) is ten times higher than in French-speaking countries (Burkina Faso, Guinea, and Benin). This has a direct impact on government policies, on social welfare programs, and on the implementation of education for all.”
